g.text: A DNS zone transfer is a full copy of all DNS records for a domain and its subdomains from one name
server to another, ensuring consistency and redundancy.
A DNS zone transfer (AXFR) involves a secondary server requesting a full zone copy from the primary
server. The primary responds with the SOA record, followed by all DNS records. Once the transfer is
complete, the secondary server acknowledges receipt.
This command asks dig to perform a full zone transfer (AXFR) from the target.com DNS server.
If misconfigured, it will reveal all DNS records, including subdomains.

IP-Based: Assigns a unique IP to each site, offering better isolation but requiring multiple IPs,
making it costly and less scalable.
Port-Based: Differentiates websites by port numbers on the same IP, useful when IPs are scarce but

Certificate Transparency (CT) logs are public, append-only ledgers tracking SSL/TLS certificate
issuance. They help detect rogue certificates, hold Certificate Authorities accountable, and
strengthen web security by ensuring transparency and oversight.
Banner Grabbing: Analyzing server banners for software details.
HTTP Headers: Extracting info like server software from headers.
Probing Responses: Sending crafted requests to reveal technologies.
Page Content Analysis: Looking for clues in page structure and scripts.
Links: Internal and external links map website structure and uncover hidden pages.
Comments: Users may reveal sensitive information or vulnerabilities.
Metadata: Page details (titles, descriptions, keywords) offer context.
Sensitive Files: Crawlers find exposed files (backups, config, logs) containing confidential data.

The Wayback Machine is a digital archive that lets users view past versions of websites. Since 1996,
it captures snapshots of websites through automated crawlers, storing content like HTML, images,
and scripts. Users can access these archived versions by entering a URL and selecting a date,
offering a glimpse into how websites looked in the past.
Automating reconnaissance enhances efficiency, scalability, consistency, and coverage. It speeds up
tasks, reduces human error, and allows for comprehensive data collection across multiple targets.
Automation also integrates easily with other tools for a streamlined process.
